# Intuition
This is similar to [Word Break](https://leetcode.com/problems/word-break/) except instead of checking if a string segment exists in a dictionary, we use a helper function to validate it.

# Approach
1. In the main backtracking loop, build up the IP address segment.
2. If the segment is invalid, don't use it.  Valid segment in this context means
a. The segment should be a value <= 255.
b. The segment cannot be left zero padded if its length > 1.
c. If we already have 3 segments in our IP address candidate, the current segment length has to be equal to the remaining length of the input string.  Remember, you have to use all the digits in the input string to form the IP address.
3. Otherwise,  backtrack.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: -

- Space complexity: -
```
# Code
/**
 * @param {string} s
 * @return {string[]}
 */
var restoreIpAddresses = function(s) {
    const result = [];
    solve(s, 0, [], result);
    return result;
};

const solve = (s, start, candidate, result) => {
    if (candidate.length === 4) {
        result.push(candidate.join('.'));
        return;
    }

    let segment = '';
    for (let i = start; i < s.length; i++) {
        segment += s[i];
        if (!isValidSegment(s, start, segment, candidate)) {
            continue;
        }
        candidate.push(segment);
        solve(s, i + 1, candidate, result);
        candidate.pop();
    }
}

const isValidSegment = (s, start, segment, candidate) => {
    if (Number(segment) > 255) {
        return false;
    }

    if (segment.length > 1 && segment[0] === '0') {
        return false;
    }

    const remainingLength = s.length - start;
    if (candidate.length === 3 && segment.length < remainingLength) {
        return false;
    }

    return true;
}
```

